    "note": "Squad cost = gross wages + per-player amortisation. This is exactly the method Calcio e Finanza use.",
    "validation": {
      "ourWageBill": "137.3M gross",
      "cfWageBill": "~141M gross (Calcio e Finanza: Inter has Serie A's highest)",
      "ourSquadCost": "195.9M",
      "cfSquadCost": "~195M for 25/26 (C&F: Milan 197M edges Inter)",
      "verdict": "within 3% — the model tracks the published figures"
    },
    "wages": "Capology / Calcio e Finanza — GROSS. mult (1.5 vs 1.84) reflects whether the player still qualifies for the Decreto Crescita tax break.",
    "amortisation": "fee ÷ contract length, from official announcements. A buy-back books the net of the two deals (Stankovic: 23 paid − 10 previously received = 13 on the books).",
    "excluded": "Agent commissions — Calcio e Finanza leave these out of amortisation too.",
    "bonuses": "Base fee only. Add-ons are contingent consideration: under IFRS a club may capitalise them when they become probable, or only once triggered. Inter's published amortisation figures use the base fee, so that's what we use."
  },
